│ corrective adjustment, causing spurious failure.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's        │
│ Log:\nThe debug log shows vectorization building large bundles involving      │
│ reused PHIs and arithmetic chains. Eventually the vectorizer evaluates costs  │
│ for a tree including reused scalars (multiple occurrences of the same         │
│ PHINodes). This reuse leads to a mask larger than the vector factor computed  │
│ for the node. The first transformation point is inside createShuffle(), and   │
│ the assertion failure matches the single-entry node path. There is no earlier │
│ IR mutation \u2013 we are still in cost estimation \u2013 confirming a logic  │
│ error in mask/CommonVF handling, not corrupted IR.\n\n3. Root Cause           │
│ Analysis:\nFor reused scalars, E->getVectorFactor() returns the effective     │
│ vector width needed to materialize the reused pattern (number of unique       │
│ lanes), while Mask.size() equals the number of scalar positions in the        │
│ original build (including duplicates). The code sets CommonVF = VF and        │
│ immediately asserts indices < CommonVF before performing the special-case     │
│ adjustment for VF != Mask.size(). This ordering is wrong: the adjustment that │
│ raises CommonVF to E->Scalars.size() (matching Mask.size()) happens only      │
│ after the assertion. Thus any mask index >= VF but < Mask.size() causes the   │
│ assertion to fail even though it is valid once CommonVF is updated. We must   │
│ move or conditionalize the assertion so that it occurs after potential mask   │
│ expansion or use an appropriate bound depending on the case.\n\n4. Proposed   │
│ Edit Points:\nEdit lines 8876-8889 of                                         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp (the single-entry node        │
│ branch). Replace the unconditional assertion with logic that:\n- First        │
│ obtains VF.\n- If we need to expand (E->Scalars.size() == Mask.size() && VF   │
│ != Mask.size()), perform the mask remap, then set CommonVF =                  │
│ E->Scalars.size(), then assert indices < CommonVF.\n- Else (no remap needed), │
│ assert indices < CommonVF (which equals VF).\nThis preserves the original     │
│ intent of validating mask indices against the final CommonVF, avoiding        │
│ premature failure.\n\nPatch Concept:\nOriginal:\n  CommonVF = VF;\n           │
│ assert(all_of(Mask, Idx < CommonVF));\n  if (E->Scalars.size() == Mask.size() │
│ && VF != Mask.size()) { remap; CommonVF = E->Scalars.size(); }\n\nModified:\n │
│ CommonVF = VF;\n  if (E->Scalars.size() == Mask.size() && VF != Mask.size())  │
│ { remap; CommonVF = E->Scalars.size(); }\n  assert(all_of(Mask, Idx <         │
│ CommonVF));\n\nRationale: After remapping CommonMask we adjust CommonVF to    │
│ the expanded size, making the assertion accurate. For the non-remap path      │
│ semantics unchanged.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy deferring the assertion until      │
│ after potential CommonVF adjustment, we correctly handle reused-scalar masks  │
│ and prevent false assertion failures during shuffle cost estimation. The fix  │
│ maintains cost logic and mask transformation semantics while eliminating the  │
│ crash for the provided reproducer and similar patterns involving reuse.\n"    │
│ }                                                                             │
